    44	whose health effects have never been causally measured, the model makes its epistemics explicit.
    45	Every effect is shrunk toward zero in proportion to how well its supporting study identifies
    46	causation, the shrinkage schedule is a slider rather than a buried constant, and the headline
    47	is reported across the full range of evidence philosophies — from counting only randomized
    48	evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
    49	The paper makes four contributions. It provides, to my knowledge, the first portfolio-level
    50	cost-effectiveness estimate for a major philanthropist: a best-guess median of 202,000 QALYs
    51	from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in 2026 dollars), a blended $150,067 per QALY, and a
    52	benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 at the U.S. government’s value per QALY (U.S. Department of Health
    53	and Human Services, Office of the Assistant Secretary for Planning and Evaluation 2026). It
    54	documents extreme geographic concentration of modeled impact: the 4.8% of dollars funding
    55	global health and development delivered outside the United States accounts for 69.1% of estimated
    56	health impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the gift data itself: across 1,313 disclosed
    57	gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift revenue to the power 0.41 (R² 0.37) —
    58	Scott’s giving is far flatter across organization size than proportional. And it demonstrates a
    59	working method for auditable, AI-assisted cost-effectiveness modeling: the model was built with
    60	a frontier language model, reviewed and corrected in public across eleven revision rounds, audited
    61	by two independent model families against primary filings, and ships with versioned parameters,
    62	machine-checked citations, and a browser implementation that reruns the full Monte Carlo under
    63	any reader’s assumptions.
    64	The unit of account deserves a caveat before any number. QALYs measure health. Most of Scott’s
    65	portfolio aims at other things — education, economic mobility, equity, civic infrastructure —
    66	whose primary benefits are not health benefits. A finding that a dollar of education philanthropy
    67	produces few QALYs is a statement about the lens, not a verdict on the gift. The estimates here
    68	are a lower bound on total wellbeing produced, measured along the one dimension with a mature
    69	comparative literature.
    70	
    71	2 Data
    72	2.1 The ledger
    73	Scott’s essays disclose giving in dated tranches totaling $26.39 billion nominal over 2020–2025.
    74	The model inflates each tranche to 2026 dollars with CPI-U, so dollars and cost-effectiveness
    75	evidence share one price level: $30.3B total. All derivations below, and the replication repository,
    76	start from a verbatim snapshot of the Yield Giving gift database retrieved July 11, 2026 (Yield
    77	Giving 2026).
    78	
    79	2
    80	
    81	2.2 Allocation across causes
    82	Scott publishes no aggregate dollars-by-cause breakdown, but she publishes better: a gift-level
    83	database listing every recipient organization, its self-reported focus areas, and — for 2,035 of 2,711
    84	gifts ($17.46B, about two-thirds of the nominal total) — the dollar amount. Each organization’s
    85	dollars are split equally across its focus areas; the database’s 53 areas map onto the model’s 14
    86	intervention archetypes under a documented, sync-tested crosswalk.
    87	The undisclosed third is imputed rather than dropped. Because the essays give each year’s
    88	total, the undisclosed residual per period is a known dollar amount; it is distributed across that
    89	period’s undisclosed gifts in proportion to each recipient’s pre-gift IRS Form 990 total revenue
    90	(ProPublica 2026), raised to an elasticity fit on the disclosed pairs. Pre-gift means the latest
    91	filing strictly before the gift year, since a Scott gift mechanically inflates receipt-year revenue.
    92	The fit is a finding in its own right: across 1,313 disclosed gift–filing pairs, log gift size rises
    93	with log revenue with slope 0.41 (R² 0.37). A 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more
    94	money, not 10× more. Fuzzy name-to-EIN matches were audited by a third, smaller model
    95	against the live IRS API, with corrections committed as a reviewable overlay. The imputed third
    96	moves each cause share by at most about 1.5 percentage points — the disclosed two-thirds is
    97	representative.
    98	
    99	2.3 Delivery geography
   100	Each organization reports service locations. Weighting disclosed dollars by the share of an
   101	organization’s locations outside the United States, an estimated 20% of disclosed dollars ($3.57
   102	billion of $17.46B) goes to organizations serving abroad, led by environment, health, and funding
   103	intermediaries. The model prices geography through a single channel: health-relevant dollars
   104	route to a global-health archetype in proportion to the recipient’s non-U.S. service share, because
   105	global health delivery is the one category with a published cost-per-QALY evidence base an
   106	order of magnitude below U.S. anchors. Education and climate dollars keep their U.S.-study
   107	anchors wherever they are delivered; if geography changes their effectiveness, the model does not
   108	capture it.
   109	The coarsest geographic field is the bare label “global.” An audit of the 50 largest organizations
   110	reporting only that label — 87% of that bucket’s dollars — replaced the blanket assumption of
   111	fully-abroad delivery with fractions taken from each organization’s own filings and program reports,
   112	independently verified by a second model family, with per-organization sources committed to the
   113	repository. Many “global” organizations operate substantially in the United States: Planned
   114	Parenthood and Crisis Text Line, for example, list “global” service but are roughly 95% and 93%
   115	U.S. by their own reporting. The audited allocation routes 4.82% of the ledger to global health
   116	and development delivered abroad.
   117	
   118	3 Model
   119	Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the
   120	derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in
   121	
   122	3
   123	
   124	published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. Causal
   125	credibility asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification
   126	tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward
   127	the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock (Cesarini et al. 2016) or the ACA Medicaid
   128	mortality quasi-experiment (Miller et al. 2021; Sommers 2017) keeps most of its effect; the
   129	community-health-center rollout design (Bailey and Goodman-Bacon 2015) and similar contested
   130	quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only categories are shrunk near zero.
   131	Realization asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers the studied effect at all —
   132	transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of the capacity effects of large
   133	unrestricted gifts that the Center for Effective Philanthropy documents for Scott’s recipients
   134	specifically (Center for Effective Philanthropy 2023). It is one global triangular draw with mode
   135	0.80 on support 0.55–1.10.
   136	The two discounts partition the doubt: transportability concerns live only in realization, identification concerns only in credibility, and cost-per-QALY priors are stated conditional on the
   137	effect being real and delivered. The tier ordering is the defensible part; the levels are judgment,
   138	proposed by a language model and reviewed by the author, and the results section reports the
   139	full consequence of disagreeing with them.
   140	Health effects arrive in different natural units — lives saved, life-years, depression-free days —
   141	and are converted to discounted QALYs under a common set of conventions (about 65 remaining
   142	life-years at baseline utility 0.87, 3% annual discounting), with every parameter’s unit and dollar
   143	vintage machine-validated at load. The global-health frontier benchmark is handicapped likefor-like: GiveWell’s current program averages (GiveWell 2026), converted to roughly $175–$241
   144	per discounted QALY-equivalent under this model’s own conventions, modeled as loguniform
   145	$150–$260, and subjected to the same realization and credibility discounts as Scott’s portfolio.
   146	
   147	4 Results
   148	Source: Article Notebook
   149	Source: Article Notebook
   150	
   151	At the best-guess defaults (100,000 draws), the portfolio produces a median of 201,923 QALYs,
   152	with a 90% interval of 94,000 to 419,000 and a mean of 222,060. The blended cost-effectiveness
   153	— dollars given over QALYs produced, at the median — is $150,067 per QALY. Monetized at
   154	the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services’ value per QALY, the health alone repays
   155	the giving 4.9 times over (90% interval 2.1–11.0). Figure 1 shows the full distribution.
   156	
   157	4.1 Where it comes from
   158	Table 1 decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper’s central fact: the global
   159	health and development slice — 4.8% of dollars — contributes 69.1% of estimated QALYs, at a
   160	realized cost of about $10,000 per QALY against $350,000–$450,000 for the large U.S. buckets.
   161	The 1,200-fold spread in realized cost-effectiveness within a single donor’s portfolio restates, in
