   579	5.3 Corrections history
   580	The model reached this state through eleven public revision rounds, and the trajectory is itself
   581	evidence about the method. Cross-model review rounds cut the headline from roughly 98,000
   582	to 87,000 QALYs (dollar-vintage normalization, a life-year/QALY conversion made explicit, a
   583	re-derived frontier benchmark, one re-attributed citation). Replacing an assumed allocation with
   584	the derivation from Scott’s own database cut it to roughly 70,000. A reader’s correction — health
   585	dollars had been priced at U.S. anchors regardless of delivery location — tripled it to roughly
   586	205,000, and the subsequent two-model geography audit settled it at 202,000. Every correction
   587	is documented in the repository and summarized on the public tool; none was caught by the
   588	author unaided, and all but one were caught by models or readers rather than the author.
   589	
   590	6 Construction and auditability
   591	The model was built with a frontier language model (Anthropic’s Claude), with the author reviewing every parameter and assumption; adversarial review by a second model family (OpenAI’s),
   592	plus reader corrections, produced the revision history above. Three mechanisms make the result
   593	checkable rather than merely stated. Parameters live in one typed file in which every value carries
   594	its unit, dollar vintage, and inline citation, machine-validated at load; an annotated bibliography
   595	maps each quantitative input to its primary source and price-level conversion. Sync tests force
   596	the published web parameters, allocation shares, geography exports, and this manuscript’s inputs
   597	to equal fresh derivations from the committed data snapshots, so prose and model cannot drift
   598	apart. And the audit trail is data: the 990 match audit and the 50-organization geography audit
   599	are committed as per-row overlay files with sources and confidence grades, applied by the pipeline
   600	rather than folded silently into parameters.
   601	The browser implementation is a checked TypeScript port that reruns the full Monte Carlo
   602	client-side; every figure in this paper can be reproduced, and every assumption overridden, at
   603	maxghenis.com/mackenzie-scott-qaly. The repository, including this manuscript’s source, is at
   604	github.com/MaxGhenis/mackenzie-scott-qaly.
   605	
   606	7 Limitations
   607	The credibility tiers and realization distribution are judgment priors with no literature calibration;
   608	the ordering is defensible, the levels are not measured, and the stance sweep is the honest bound
   609	on their influence. The QALY lens counts only health, so the estimate is a floor on total wellbeing,
   610	and the causes where Scott concentrates — education, mobility, equity — are precisely those
   611	whose main benefits the lens excludes. Credibility shrinks toward zero but never below it, so the
   612	model places no mass on harmful giving. Allocation splits each organization’s dollars equally
   613	across its focus areas and service locations; both are coarse, and the geography audit covers only
   614	the 50 largest “global”-listed organizations. Realization is one global draw, so it cannot vary
   615	by cause. Archetype anchors treat heterogeneous organizations as draws from one distribution.
   616	Within each cause, delivery regions are priced identically, so the geographic decomposition
   617	exposes assumptions rather than measuring regional differences. The undisclosed third of dollars
   618	
